WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
6 New Year English

2
00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:05.000
From BBCLearningEnglish.com

3
00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Hello, this is 6 Minute English from BBCLearningEnglish. I'm Phil

4
00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:14.000
And I'm Bacca

5
00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:16.000
6 Minute English listeners are truly global

6
00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:20.000
Coming from all over the world including some of the coldest countries on earth

7
00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:25.000
Places like Finland where winter temperatures drop to minus 20 degrees Celsius

8
00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:28.000
Are you good at dealing with the cold fill?

9
00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:32.000
I'm not sure but I do know that I don't like it. What about you Bacca?

10
00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:38.000
Well, I'd rather be too hot and cool down than too cold and try to warm up

11
00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:43.000
Yes, me too. Here in the UK it never gets as cold as Finland

12
00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:49.000
But it's not unusual to see some people dressed in t-shirts while others are wrapped up in warm clothes

13
00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:53.000
Why do people feel the cold so differently?

14
00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:55.000
That's what we'll be discussing in this episode

15
00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:59.000
As well as learning some useful new words and phrases

16
00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:02.000
And as always you'll find all the vocabulary from this episode

17
00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:05.000
Plus a quiz and worksheet on our website

18
00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:07.000
BBCLearningEnglish.com

19
00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:09.000
But now I have a question for you Bacca

20
00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:12.000
According to the Guinness Book of World Records

21
00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:18.000
The lowest temperature ever recorded was a very cold minus 89 degrees Celsius

22
00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:20.000
But where?

23
00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:22.000
Was it A the Arctic?

24
00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:24.000
B Antarctica?

25
00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:27.000
Or C the top of Mount Everest?

26
00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:31.000
I'm going to guess B Antarctica.

27
00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:35.000
Okay, well we'll find out the answer at the end of the program

28
00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:42.000
Our experience of cold depends on many things including our genes, culture and place of birth

29
00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:47.000
But perhaps the most obvious thing is the clothes we wear

30
00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:52.000
Professor Ghanin Sartron lives on the icy island of Svalbard

31
00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:55.000
800 miles inside the Arctic Circle

32
00:01:55.000 --> 00:02:01.000
Here she advises presenter Caroline Steele on how to dress against the cold

33
00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:05.000
For BBC World Service program crowd science

34
00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:09.000
So what should we consider when choosing our clothes?

35
00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:15.000
First of all, I would say that perhaps the gender differs

36
00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:19.000
So may you love to know more tolerant perhaps in females?

37
00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:21.000
Then it's of course what you use to?

38
00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:23.000
Are you used to dealing with the cold?

39
00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:25.000
Are you not?

40
00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:28.000
Ghanin says that first and foremost men and women

41
00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:30.000
Filled the cold differently.

42
00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:35.000
She uses the phrase first and foremost to mean more than anything else

43
00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:38.000
She wants to emphasise that something in this case

44
00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:41.000
Someone's gender is the most important thing to consider

45
00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:47.000
There is some debate about whether men or women are more tolerant of the cold

46
00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:52.000
Being tolerant of something means being able to endure it without getting hurt

47
00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:56.000
Another important factor is whether you are used to the cold

48
00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:00.000
If being in cold environments is something you're familiar with

49
00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:04.000
It might sound obvious that someone born in Arctic Svalbard

50
00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:07.000
Would feel less cold than someone born in Brazil

51
00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:10.000
But apart from environmental factors

52
00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:15.000
Are the actual physical differences that allow people to cope better with the cold?

53
00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:19.000
Dr. Kara Ocobok studies reindeer herders in northern Finland

54
00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:23.000
People who live in cold temperatures every day and have done for centuries

55
00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:28.000
She measures their reaction to extreme cold and compares it to ordinary fins

56
00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:30.000
From warmer parts of the country

57
00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:34.000
Here, Kara shares her findings with Caroline Still

58
00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:37.000
From BBC World Services Crowd Science

59
00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:42.000
Okay, and my guess is the reindeer herders Dale Bata in the cold?

60
00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:44.000
Yes and no!

61
00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:50.000
The more data we collect within this area, the more confusing the picture gets

62
00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:53.000
I can say that subjectively at this point

63
00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:58.000
The reindeer herders at least kind of mentally handle the cold far better

64
00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:00.000
They are far less likely to shiver

65
00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:05.000
So, do the reindeer herders deal better with the cold?

66
00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:08.000
The answer is yes and no

67
00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:11.000
A phrase meaning partly and partly not

68
00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:14.000
Used when there's no clear answer to a question

69
00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:21.000
However, Kara does say, subjectively the herders manage better

70
00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:23.000
They don't feel so cold

71
00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:27.000
Subjectively means based on your personal inner experience

72
00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:30.000
Rather than objective facts

73
00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:33.000
And physically, there are differences too

74
00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:36.000
The reindeer herders are less likely to shiver

75
00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:41.000
The shaky movement that cold muscles make to try and warm them up

76
00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:47.000
In fact, how we experience the cold is probably a combination of everything we've discussed

77
00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:51.000
Including genetic adaptations passed on from parents to children

78
00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:54.000
Right, I'm off to find my gloves and Willy Hat

79
00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:57.000
So why don't you reveal the answer to the question fill?

80
00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:02.000
Yes, I asked where the lowest temperature on earth was ever recorded

81
00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:07.000
You said B and Antarctica and that is the right answer

82
00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:12.000
The lowest temperature ever recorded on earth was at the Vostock Research Station

83
00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:15.000
In Antarctica in 1983

84
00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:18.000
Let's recap the vocabulary we've learnt

85
00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:21.000
Starting with the phrase first and foremost

86
00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:23.000
Meaning more than anything else

87
00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:29.000
A person who is tolerant of something is able to endure it without being hurt

88
00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:33.000
If you're used to something, you're familiar with it

89
00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:37.000
The idiom yes and no means partly and partly not

90
00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:41.000
And is used when you can't give a clear answer to a question

91
00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:46.000
The advert subjectively means in a way that's based on your personal experience

92
00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:48.000
Rather than objective facts

93
00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:52.000
And finally, a shiver is the shaking movement made by your muscles

94
00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:54.000
When you feel cold or afraid

95
00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:57.000
Once again, our six minutes are up

96
00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:02.000
But remember, you'll find a quiz and a worksheet for this episode on our website

97
00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:04.000
BBCLearningEnglish.com

98
00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:07.000
See you there soon, but for now it's goodbye

99
00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:08.000
Bye
